🎬 STORY: “USER LOGS INTO A BANKING APP ON iOS”

We go step-by-step, like real life.

🎬 SCENE 1: APP LAUNCH
Flow:
User taps app icon
→ iOS verifies code signature
→ App process starts inside sandbox

🧩 Component: Code Signing + Sandbox

🔐 What happens?
-> Only Apple-signed apps can run
-> App gets isolated container

💣 Threat: Jailbroken Device
Q. Why?
-> Code signing enforcement can be bypassed
Q. Impact?
-> Run modified app
-> Inject malicious code

🛡️ Mitigation
- Jailbreak detection
- Runtime integrity checks

🎬 SCENE 2: LOGIN FLOW
Flow:
User enters credentials
→ App calls backend (HTTPS)
→ Token received
→ Stored in Keychain

🧩 Component: Keychain
🔐 What it does?
Encrypted storage tied to device + Secure Enclave

💣 Threat: Insecure Storage
-> Bad practice:
Store token in UserDefaults
Because
UserDefaults = plaintext

🛡️ Mitigation
Use Keychain with:
kSecAttrAccessibleWhenUnlocked

🎬 SCENE 3: DEEP LINK ENTRY (CRITICAL ATTACK SURFACE)
Flow:
bankapp://transfer?amount=10000

🧩 Component: URL Schemes / Universal Links

💣 Threat: Deep Link Hijacking
Attack:
Malicious app registers same scheme
Q. Why Dangerous?
-> Because iOS picks one app (not guaranteed yours)

🛡️ Mitigation
-> Use Universal Links (domain verified)
-> Validate parameters server-side

🎬 SCENE 4: INTER-PROCESS COMMUNICATION
Flow:
App A → App B (via URL / XPC)

🧩 Component: XPC / URL schemes

💣 Threat: Data Injection
Attack:
Attacker sends crafted data
Q. Why Dangerous?
-> App trusts incoming data

🛡️ Mitigation
-> Validate ALL inputs
-> Authenticate requests

🎬 SCENE 5: RUNTIME (DYNAMIC NATURE OF iOS)
Flow:
App executes Swift/Obj-C code

🧩 Component: Objective-C Runtime

💣 Threat: Method Swizzling / Hooking
Attack:
Using tools like: Frida / Cycript
Attacker modifies:
isUserLoggedIn() → always true
Q. Why it is possible?
Ans: Because Runtime is dynamic

🛡️ Mitigation
- Runtime integrity checks
- Detect hooking frameworks

🎬 SCENE 6: NETWORK COMMUNICATION
Flow:
App → HTTPS → Backend
🔐 Security
TLS encryption
💣 Threat: MITM
Attack
Install rogue certificate
Intercept traffic
Why
System trusts installed CAs
🛡️ Mitigation
Certificate pinning
🎬 SCENE 7: KERNEL ENFORCEMENT
🧩 Component: XNU Kernel
🔐 What it enforces
- Sandbox
- Code signing
- Memory protection
💣 Threat: Kernel Exploit
Why
Kernel has highest privileges
🛡️ Mitigation
OS updates
Exploit mitigations (ASLR, DEP)
🎬 SCENE 8: SECURE ENCLAVE (ROOT OF TRUST)
🧩 Component: Secure Enclave
🔐 What it does
Stores cryptographic keys
Performs biometric auth
💣 Threat

Very hard → physical attack

🛡️ Mitigation
Use Secure Enclave-backed keys
💥 FULL REAL-WORLD ATTACK CHAIN
1. Attacker installs malicious app
2. Exploits deep link → triggers sensitive action
3. Hooks runtime (Frida)
4. Bypasses authentication checks
5. Extracts token from insecure storage
6. Performs MITM attack
7. Calls backend APIs as victim


🧠 KEY DIFFERENCE vs ANDROID
iOS is stricter by design
- Mandatory sandbox
- Strong code signing
- Limited IPC
BUT still vulnerable at app layer
- Deep links
- Storage
- Runtime hooking
